{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d3f3a576-1a2c-4ee1-ac9a-66bf46132d66","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance from .NET/macOS knowledge:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores`):\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/cores/core.%P\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** A `core.<pid>` file should appear in `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If SIP (System Integrity Protection) blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily disable it or use the `lldb` approach instead:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --attach-pid <pid>\n   # after crash:\n   process save-core /path/to/dump.core\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app /cores/core.<pid>\n   bt all   # get all thread backtraces\n   ```\n\n**Key macOS caveats:**\n- SIP can prevent core dump generation for certain binaries.\n- NativeAOT apps don't bundle `createdump`, so you rely on OS-level facilities.\n- Ensure your app is built with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) for meaningful stack traces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"91116a3d-70f0-495b-866b-4c95f9ce4908","outputTokens":335,"requestId":"74C3:19B167:E2AAA8:10A02D7:69FE92A9"},"id":"59e38055-bc13-4b20-813c-fe5a8723581f","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:49:44.538Z","parentId":"bf14b991-080e-4a21-9819-be62a54ff078"}
